  "plot_summary": "[HANG0] * This month's <i>Marvel Bullpen Bulletins</i> mentions a friendly lunch between Stan Lee and DC Comics' Carmine Infantino, who is described as Stan's counterpart over \"there.\"&nbsp; (The pair would later oversee the pairing of both companies most popular heroes, but that doesn't come for several more years!)\n\n[HANG0] * John Buscema's return to the <i>Avengers</i> is announced.\n\n[HANG0] * <i>MBB</i> mentions that Roy Thomas and his wife Jean travelled to Las Vegas, also stopping to see Gary Friedrich, who now sports a mustache and is recently married.\n\n[HANG0] * <i>MBB</i> also mentions a strange habit of Gene Colan, who pauses on the phone to introduce himself every time he calls in, as if no one there remembers him<i>, heh</i>.\n\n[HANG0] * In what seems to be an obvious mistake, the books were published this month with two copies of the <i>Mighty Marvel Checklist</i>, one on a page that shared space with the same half-page ad about the MarvelMania International club that had been published the <i>previous</i> month (and that I mentioned in last month's monthly roundup).&nbsp; The other was part of the <i>Marvel Bullpen Bulletins</i>.&nbsp; This seemed like such a blatant  error that, at first, I did not believe my digital scans were correct, but as I still had a physical copy of [LINK:1970:SUB_24|SUB #24] to check, I pulled it out and flipped through it.&nbsp; And there it was, exactly as shown in the digital copy.&nbsp; Marvel made a boneheaded error, this standalone version, advertising the books from <i>last month</i>!&nbsp; <i>Heh</i>...<b><i>oops</i></b>!\n\n[HANG0] * And speaking of errors, even the <i>correct</i> version of the <i>Checklist</i> contains an error, talking about Suprema as part of this month's [LINK:1970:CAP_124|CAP #124], which anyone knows was who Cap was up against <i>last</i> month.&nbsp; No mention is made of this month's MODOK or Cyborg.&nbsp; Not only that, but the new text didn't even match the text from the erroneously-included version in the <i>other</i> copy advertising last month's issue, meaning someone went to the trouble of describing the old issue a second time.\n\n[HANG0] * <i>Stan's Soapbox</i> this month focuses on the role that \"moralizing\" plays in the published books, his own take on the matter being that: <i>a story without a message, however subliminal, is like a man without a soul</i>.&nbsp; This seems to be in response to feedback complaining that many feel comics should be more of \"escapist reading\" and not a commentary on the events of the day.\n\n[HANG0] * This being the first publication month of the year (Jan, 1970), the annual \"Statement of Ownership\" notice appears in most books this month, often at the bottom of one of the letters pages.\n\n[HANG0] * While not an announcement, it's worth calling out this month's issue of <i>Chamber of Darkness</i>, which includes a story (\"The Monster!\") written <i>and</i> drawn by Jack Kirby, but even <i>that</i> is not all that is noteworthy in this issue, as it also features a tale called \"The Sword and the Sorcerers!\" by Roy Thomas and Barry Smith, involving a character named Starr the Slayer - who seems to be very proto-Conan-like.",
